    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1971-09-28T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1971-09-28T00:00:00-05:00" n="200"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d200">
                <head>200. Memorandum From the Chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff (<persName
                        corresp="#p_MTH1" type="from">Moorer</persName>) to Secretary of Defense
                        <persName corresp="#p_LMR1" type="to">Laird</persName>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d200fn1">Source: National Archives, <gloss
                            target="#t_RG1">RG</gloss> 218, Records of the Joint Chiefs of Staff,
                            <persName corresp="#p_MTH1">Moorer</persName>, 388.3, <gloss
                            target="#t_SALT1">SALT</gloss>, July–December 1971. Top Secret;
                        Sensitive.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">CM–1232–71</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1971-09-28">September 28, 1971</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJ</head>
                    <item>
                        <gloss target="#t_SALT1">SALT</gloss> Developments</item>
                </list>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>I have been concerned by the course of <gloss target="#t_SALT1"
                            >SALT</gloss> since the announcement of the 20 May 1971 understanding.
                        Of particular concern to me has been the undiminished momentum of all Soviet
                            programs—<gloss target="#t_ICBM1">ICBM</gloss>, <gloss target="#t_SLBM1"
                            >SLBM</gloss>, and <gloss target="#t_ABM1">ABM</gloss>—contrasted with
                        an unyielding Soviet negotiating stance. As you know, on instructions, the
                            <gloss target="#t_US1">U.S</gloss>. <gloss target="#t_SALT1"
                            >SALT</gloss> Delegation rejected all four Soviet <gloss
                            target="#t_ABM1">ABM</gloss> proposals while the Soviets have not
                        accepted the <gloss target="#t_US1">U.S</gloss>. “two or one” proposal. The
                        Soviets insist that an <gloss target="#t_ABM1">ABM</gloss> Agreement must be
                        reached this year, prior to agreement on certain offensive limitations.
                        Therefore, the Soviets have not discussed offensive limitations in any
                        detail, but have said that <gloss target="#t_SLBM1">SLBM</gloss>s must be
                        excluded from an interim freeze on strategic offensive weapons.</item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>In my opinion, the Soviets feel that the <gloss target="#t_US1"
                            >U.S</gloss>. will accede to an <gloss target="#t_ABM1">ABM</gloss>
                        Agreement on Soviet terms and then an interim freeze on <gloss
                            target="#t_ICBM1">ICBM</gloss>s only. I feel they are holding an <gloss
                            target="#t_SLBM1">SLBM</gloss> freeze in abeyance as leverage to get
                            <gloss target="#t_US1">U.S</gloss>. concessions on FBS in later
                        negotiations. The Soviets seem to feel that pressure is on the <gloss
                            target="#t_US1">U.S</gloss>. to make concessions and, therefore, they
                        need to make none. In the meantime, the ongoing Soviet programs continue to
                        affect adversely the strategic balance from the <gloss target="#t_US1"
                            >U.S</gloss>. point of view.</item>
                    <label>3.</label>
                    <item>I recommend that we hold fast to our basic objectives in <gloss
                            target="#t_SALT1">SALT</gloss> and to require forward movement by the
                        Soviets with respect to offensive restraints prior to signing any defensive
                        agreement.</item>
                </list>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_MTH1">
                            <hi rend="strong">T.H. Moorer</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
